{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17500079","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17500079"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:08:33+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:08:33+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1606"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1606","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1606"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.22,0.61,0.03,0.13,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1606"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67282"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1606","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1606"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1606"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52734"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"665"},{"type":"tags","id":"1036"},{"type":"tags","id":"1114"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"8118"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2136"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11883"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11899"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17193"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17422"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17423"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17446"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42351"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44580"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67282","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/67282"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 54-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a one-hour history of severe, constant, tearing chest pain radiating to his neck and between the shoulder blades. He has a 12-year history of hypertension but regularly forgets to take his medication. His regular medications are amlodipine and olmesartan.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears distressed with a pulse rate of 110/min, blood pressure 175/110 mmHg in the right arm and 145/100 mmHg in the left arm, respiratory rate 24/min, and temperature 37.1\u00b0C. His JVP is 8 cm. An ECG shows 2 mm ST elevation in leads V1-3. His chest X-ray is shown (Image).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELaboratory tests reveal a D-dimer level of 1.5 mg/L (\u0026lt;0.5) and a troponin level of 0.04 ng/mL (\u0026lt;0.01).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which of the following would be the most appropriate next step for making a definitive diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Transesophageal echocardiography","Computed tomography angiography","Magnetic resonance angiography","Transthoracic echocardiography","Digital subtraction angiography"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe clinical presentation of severe, tearing chest pain radiating to the back, along with the blood pressure discrepancy between arms and the widened mediastinum on chest X-ray, strongly suggests an aortic dissection. ST segment changes may occur with an aortic dissection. While the troponin and D-dimer levels are elevated, this can occur in aortic dissection; furthermore, these levels are not significantly elevated. Overall, therefore, myocardial infarction and pulmonary embolism are less likely diagnoses.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe most appropriate next step for definitive diagnosis is \u003Cstrong\u003Ecomputed tomography angiography (CTA)\u003C/strong\u003E. CTA is the gold standard for diagnosing aortic dissection as it provides detailed images of the aorta, allowing for the identification of an intimal flap and the extent of the dissection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETransesophageal echocardiography\u003C/strong\u003E is another diagnostic tool that can be used to assess aortic dissection, especially in unstable patients who cannot be moved to the CT scanner. However, it is not as widely available as CTA and may not provide as comprehensive a view of the entire aorta.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMagnetic resonance angiography (MRA)\u003C/strong\u003E can also be used to diagnose aortic dissection, but it is less commonly used in the acute setting due to longer scan times and limited availability in emergency situations. Magnetic resonance angiography requires reasonably specialised radiographers and not all MR technicians will be trained to perform vascular imaging, thus further limiting availability in the acute setting.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETransthoracic echocardiography\u003C/strong\u003E is less sensitive for detecting aortic dissection compared to transesophageal echocardiography and CTA, as it may not adequately visualise the entire aorta.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAortography\u003C/strong\u003E was historically used for diagnosing aortic dissection but has largely been replaced by less invasive and more accurate imaging modalities like CTA.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Acute chest pain with a tearing quality and radiating to the back suggests aortic dissection.","Computed tomography angiography is the gold standard for diagnosing aortic dissection."],"references":["Senser EM, Misra S, Henkin S. Thoracic Aortic Aneurysm A Clinical Review ol Clin. 2021;39:505-15. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/34686263/","Levy D, Sharma S, Grigorova Y, et al. Aortic Dissection. [Updated 2024 Oct 6]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK441963/","Yuan, X., Mitsis, A., \u0026 Nienaber, C. A. Current understanding of aortic dissection. 2022. Life, 12(10), 1606. Available from: https://doi.org/10.3390/life12101606"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52734"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1606"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"16085"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"16085","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/16085"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/43a1fd19-cc9d-4057-9d46-3bdb6e1804be.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/43a1fd19-cc9d-4057-9d46-3bdb6e1804be.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":500,"height":440}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52734","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/52734"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-04T16:10:40+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-04T16:11:42+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1606"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67282"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}